{{US-edu-stub}}

'''English Plus''' is an [[United States|American]] [[cultural movement|movement]] formed in reaction to the [[English-only movement]]. The intent was to promote greater acceptance of [[Languages of the United States|language diversity in the United States]] in order to encourage a broader American cultural development and more international perspectives. This would be achieved by encouraging education in English as well as secondary languages across the entire population, for immigrants and natives alike. This movement has been supported by language education professionals<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncte.org/cccc/resources/positions/123796.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726173538/http://www.ncte.org/cccc/resources/positions/123796.htm |archivedate=July 26, 2008 |title=The National Language Policy |publisher=Conference on College Composition and Communication |date=March 1988}}</ref> and minority language advocacy groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lulac.org/advocacy/issues/language/aaonly.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081129141405/http://www.lulac.org/advocacy/issues/language/aaonly.html |archivedate=November 29, 2008 |title=Action Alert: House Passes English Only and Repeal of Bilingual Ballots; Urge Your Senators to Reject this Divisive Legislation Now |publisher=League of United Latin American Citizens |date=August 2, 1996}}</ref>
"English Plus" resolutions have been passed in the U.S. states of New Mexico,<ref>[http://www.ped.state.nm.us/BilingualMulticultural/dl09/New%20Mexico%20--%20English%20Plus%20Resolution.pdf Supporting Language Rights in the United States]</ref> Oregon, Rhode Island, and Washington.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewelling |first=Vickie W. |url=http://www.cal.org/resources/archive/digest/1992englishplus.html |title=English Plus |publisher=CAL |id=ED350884 |date=December 1992 |accessdate=2010-02-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724024953/http://www.cal.org/resources/archive/digest/1992englishplus.html |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref>
==History== The term "English Plus" originated in a 1985 letter to then-[[United States Secretary of Education|Secretary of Education]] [[William Bennett]] from the [[Spanish American League Against Discrimination]].<ref>{{harvnb|Crawford|1992|p=217}}</ref> {{quote|We fear that Secretary Bennett has lost sight of the fact that English is a key to equal educational opportunity, necessary but not sufficient. English by itself is not enough. Not English Only, English Plus! ...
Bennett is wrong. We won't accept English Only for our children. We want English plus. English plus math. Plus science. Plus social studies. Plus equal educational opportunities. English plus competence in the home language. Tell Bennett to enforce bilingual education and civil rights laws you enacted, or tell the President he cannot do his job. English Plus for everyone!}}
