{{angbr|{{IPA|ř}}}}, for the [[Voiced alveolar fricative trill|Czech fricative trill]], and {{angbr|{{IPA|ɛ̈}}}}, replacing {{angbr|{{IPA|ä}}}}, were added, following their approval in 1909.{{sfnp|Passy|1909}} Though not included in the chart, {{angbr|{{IPA|ɱ}}}} was mentioned as an optional symbol for the [[labiodental nasal]]. {{angbr|{{IPA|ɹ}}}} was still designated as the "provisional" symbol for the alveolar tap/flap. {{angbr|{{IPA|σ, ƍ}}}} were defined as the Bantu sounds with "tongue position of '''θ, ð''', combined with strong lip-rounding". {{angbr|{{IPA|ʜ, {{sc2|Q}}}}}} were still included though not in the chart.{{sfnp|Association phonétique internationale|1912|p=12}} {{angbr|{{IPA|ᴙ}}}} was removed entirely.

For the first time, affricates, or {{"'}}[a]ssibilated' consonant groups, i.&nbsp;e. groups in which the two elements are so closely connected that the whole might be treated as a single sound", were noted as able to be represented with a [[tie (typography)|tie bar]], as in {{angbr|{{IPA|t͡ʃ, d͜z}}}}. [[Palatalization (phonetics)|Palatalized]] consonants could be marked by a [[dot (diacritic)|dot]] above the letter, as in {{angbr|{{IPA|ṡ, ṅ, ṙ}}}}, "suggesting the connexion with the sounds '''i''' and '''j'''".{{sfnp|Association phonétique internationale|1912|p=13}}

{{angbr|{{IPA|{{resize|50%|⊢}}, {{resize|50%|⊣}}}}}} were no longer mentioned.

==1921 chart==
The 1921 ''Écriture phonétique internationale'' introduced new symbols, some of which were never to be seen in any other booklet:{{sfnp|Association phonétique internationale|1921|p=6}}

